Thanks man, glad you liked them! Honestly, as cliched as it sounds I'd say just write what you feel like. I think the nice part about writing material with anthros is you get to choose how much or little to focus on the animal traits. For me, stories are either situation first (like a water park as a setting) or the anthros first (pretty much anything with wolves). You know, I've often wondered the same thing about using greentext there. The only thing that I can think is that the standard format of the site makes the text area too wide. If you don't use short lines it makes the story look like a horrific unapproachable wall of text. Greentext gets around this (IMHO). You can get around this by posting on other sites and linking here, but stories that are posted directly to the thread get more responses, and therefore praise, incentivizing our particular way of doing things. If I ever get around to writing stuff here after I finish my other writihg projects maybe I'll do some standard from stuff. I never did much with greentexts.
I appreciate your points.

People writing greentext who write terribly on purpose are doing it wrong.
I quite like the greentext format because it's much easier to visually distinct from one type of thing to another type of thing.
For instance, some anons'll write all the dialog in normal text but leave everything else to greentext, or only have the protagonists dialog be greentext. Serves for more flexibility especially when you can't italicize or bold text. There shouldn't be any effect to the body of writing because of the greentext if you're doing it right.
